===Mini-camp and OTAs===
A mandatory three-day mini-camp was held in early May.<ref name=12punch>{{cite news |author= Associated Press|authorlink= Associated Press |title= Steelers hoping Parker, rookie Mendenhall can provide 1-2 punch|url= http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d8081eeb7&template=with-video&confirm=true|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-05-05|accessdate=2008-05-31}}</ref> [[Hines Ward]], [[Aaron Smith (American football)|Aaron Smith]] and [[Troy Polamalu]] attended the camp, but did not fully participate because of injuries.<ref>{{cite video |people= Scott Brown|title= Steelers mini-camp|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/images/video/multimedia.php?res=hi&v=2066&1=1|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|accessdate= 2008-06-05|time= 0:04}}</ref> First round draft pick, [[Rashard Mendenhall]] was welcomed by Steelers current running back [[Willie Parker]].<ref name=12punch/> Parker was "surprised" when he heard a running back was selected in the first round, but hoped to work with Mendenhall like [[Jerome Bettis]] worked with Parker during his rookie season.<ref name=ParkMend>{{cite news |first= James|last= Walker|authorlink= |title= Parker happily showing Mendenhall the Steelers' way|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/columns/story?columnist=walker_james&id=3383512 |publisher= ESPN.com|date= 2008-05-06|accessdate=2008-06-02}}</ref> During the mini-camp, the offense experimented with formations using Parker and Mendenhall in the backfield simultaneously.<ref name=ParkMend/> Receiver Hines Ward took a similar approach to Parker's in welcoming second round draft pick [[Limas Sweed]]. As with other receivers in the past, Ward was "very hands-on with Sweed throughout the weekend".<ref name=ParkMend/> Coach Mike Tomlin called the new draft picks "humble", adding that he liked their "spirit and attitude"; however, it was too early to tell how well they will ultimately perform.<ref>{{cite video |people= [[Mike Tomlin]]|title= Camp wraps up|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/images/video/multimedia.php?res=hi&v=2075&1=1|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|accessdate= 2008-06-05|time= 0:57}}</ref>

The team held two Organized Team Activities (OTAs) prior to the draft,<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Holmes pans offseason drills|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08164/889325-66.stm |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-06-12|accessdate=2008-06-12}}</ref> in addition to 12 throughout May and June.<ref>{{cite video |people= Scott Brown|year2= 2008|title= Steelers mini-camp|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/images/video/multimedia.php?res=hi&v=2066&1=1|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|accessdate= 05|accessmonth= 06|accessyear= 2008|time= 1:25}}</ref> The OTAs were voluntary, however, most players did attend.<ref name=HockeyFight>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Two fights develop; it's hockey day for Steelers|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08157/887517-66.stm |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-06-05|accessdate=2008-06-05}}</ref> Many players routinely worked on their conditioning and strength together, in addition to "informal" on field training.<ref name=HockeyFight/> A week prior to the end of OTAs Mike Tomlin said he was happy with the team's progress during the sessions. Also stating, <U+201C>We are having a productive off-season and that is what we are here for. We are here to get better individually and collectively and I think we are doing that.<U+201D><ref name=OTApleased>{{cite news |first= Teresa|last= Varley|title= Pleased with their progress|url=http://news.steelers.com/article/90009/ |publisher= Steelers.com|date= 2008-06-06|accessdate=2008-06-06}}</ref> Limas Sweed experimented on [[American football positions#Special teams|special teams]] play for the first time ever, with a concentration in [[Punt (football)|punt]] blocking.<ref name=OTApleased/> On the day of the final OTA, June 12, Tomlin stated that while he was pleased with the progress of the team, no positions would be gained or lost based on the voluntary camp. Tomlin added, "it's been teach-oriented, it's been skill-develop-oriented. It's different than playing the game of football."<ref name=NoJobs>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Tomlin says no jobs won in spring, without hitting|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08165/889666-66.stm?cmpid=sports.xml |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-06-13|accessdate=2008-06-13}}</ref> The team was given 44&nbsp;days off until the beginning of training camp.<ref name=NoJobs/>

===Off-field activity===
In May, [[ESPN The Magazine]] released the findings of its annual survey of over 80,000&nbsp;fans entitled the "Ultimate Standings: Fan Satisfaction Ranking." The Steelers ranked as the 25th best major league sports franchise out of 122&nbsp;teams from [[Major League Baseball|MLB]], [[National Football League|NFL]], [[National Basketball Association|NBA]], and the [[National Hockey League|NHL]]. The franchise finished one position behind the cross-town hockey team [[Pittsburgh Penguins]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ultimate Standings: Fan Satisfaction Rankings |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chat/sportsnation/mag/franchiseRanks |publisher=[[ESPN The Magazine]]|accessdate=2008-10-08}}</ref>  The Steelers were sixth among all NFL teams.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ultimate Standings: Fan Satisfaction Rankings - NFL |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chat/sportsnation/mag/franchiseRanks?sport=nfl&year=2008|publisher= ESPN The Magazine|accessdate=2008-10-08}}</ref> In August, ESPN.com ranked Steelers' fans as the best in the National Football League, citing their "unbelievable" sellout streak of 299&nbsp;consecutive games.<ref>{{cite news |title= ESPN ranks Steelers fans No. 1|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_585606.html?source=rss&feed=3|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-08-30|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Matt|last= Mosley|title= NFL's best fans? We gotta hand it to Steelers (barely)|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/preview08/columns/story?id=3530077|publisher= ESPN.com|date= 2008-08-29|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref>

During the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] [[2007<U+2013>08 Pittsburgh Penguins season#Stanley Cup Playoffs|run for the Stanley Cup]] multiple members of the Steelers showed support for the cross-town team.<ref>{{cite news |first= Teresa|last= Varley|title= Steelers have plenty of praise for the Penguins|url=http://news.steelers.com/article/90558/ |publisher= Steelers.com|date= 2008-06-06|accessdate=2008-06-06}}</ref> Ben Roethlisberger attended [[2008 NHL Finals|games]] in [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]], where he and the Steelers won [[Super Bowl XL]] three years prior.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Steelers Notebook: Big Ben gets Stanley Cup fever|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08142/883440-66.stm |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-05-21|accessdate=2008-05-22}}</ref> [[Mike Tomlin]] watched Game Six of [[2008 Stanley Cup Finals|the finals]] outside [[Mellon Arena]], along with 3,000&nbsp;other fans, on a [[JumboTron]] which had been erected for fans unable to acquire tickets to the sold-out game.<ref>{{cite news |first= Dan|last= Majors |title= Penguins' faithful assemble at arena|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08157/887600-61.stm |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-06-05|accessdate=2008-06-06}}</ref> [[Kevin Colbert]], [[Charlie Batch]], and Tomlin attended many games throughout the regular season.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Steelers and Pirates supporting Penguins in big way|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08143/883866-66.stm |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-05-22|accessdate=2008-05-22}}</ref> In September, Penguins' coach [[Michel Therrien]] attended the Steelers' first game of the season.<ref>{{cite news |title= Pens Coach Has Big Football Weekend|url= http://penguins.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=381460|publisher= PittsburghPenguins.com|date= 2008-09-08|accessdate=2008-09-08}}</ref>

On February 17, [[Ernie Holmes]], who played for the Steelers from 1972 to 1977, was killed in a [[Car accident|car crash]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Rooney: 'Holmes Will Be Missed By Steelers Family'|url= http://kdka.com/steelers/Steelers.Ernie.Holmes.2.632928.html|publisher= KDKA|date= 2008-02-18|accessdate=2008-09-06}}</ref> Ten days later, on February 27, award-winning journalist, Steelers radio announcer of 35 years, and inventor of the [[Terrible Towel]], [[Myron Cope]], died at age 79.<ref>{{cite news |first= Collier|last= Gene|title= Remembering Myron Cope: He spoke for Steelers Nation in a language all his own|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08059/861127-66.stm |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-02-28|accessdate=2008-06-06}}</ref> On June 6, [[Dwight White]], a defensive end on the [[Steel Curtain]] died from a blood clot. Upon his death, Dan Rooney called White, "one of the greatest players to ever wear a Steelers uniform."<ref>{{cite news  |title= Former Steeler Dwight White dies|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08158/887963-100.stm |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-06-06|accessdate=2008-06-06}}</ref> A pre-game ceremony was held in their honor prior to the first game of the season.<ref>{{cite news |first= Gerry|last= Dulac|title= Posthumous tributes|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08249/909626-66.stm|work= Steelers Notebook: Baker's stock on rise|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-09-05|accessdate=2008-09-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Steelers pay tribute to legends|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_587075.html|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-09-08|accessdate=2008-09-08}}</ref>

===Training camp===
[[National Football League Training Camp|Training camp]] was held at [[Saint Vincent College]], in [[Latrobe, Pennsylvania]], for the 42nd consecutive year.<ref>{{cite news |first= Colin|last= Dunlap|title= Saint Vincent is in top shape for Steelers|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08198/897239-66.stm?cmpid=sports.xml|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-07-16|accessdate=2008-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Paul|last= Paterra|title= St. Vincent puts on game-day face for Steelers|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_577787.html|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-07-16|accessdate=2008-07-18}}</ref> Players reported on July 27,<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= REPORTING DAY: Mike Tomlin heads into his second training camp|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08209/899904-66.stm|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-07-27|accessdate=2008-07-28}}</ref> practices commenced the following day and ran through August 17.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.steelers.com/article/90554/|title= Steelers 2008 Training Camp Information|accessdate=2008-06-13 |publisher= Steelers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3441450|title= 2008 Training camp schedule|accessdate=2008-06-24 |author= |date= 2008-06-19|publisher= ESPN.com}}</ref> Throughout the twenty three day span, seventeen included practices;<ref>{{cite news |first= Dan|last= Stefano|title= Summer vacation isn't always a break for Steelers|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/s_572847.html|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-06-15|accessdate=2008-06-16}}</ref> making the camp one of the shortest in Steelers history.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= '08 camp to be one of shortest|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08157/887518-66.stm|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-06-05|accessdate=2008-06-05}}</ref> The camp was less demanding under Tomlin, who was in his second year as coach. "We are a veteran team in some areas. You have to approach it differently because of that," said Tomlin.<ref>{{cite news |first= Scott|last= Brown|title= Tomlin plans less demanding training camp|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_572502.html|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-06-13|accessdate=2008-06-13}}</ref>

Pittsburgh looked to build on their defense, which was ranked first in the league throughout the 2007 season. At over thirty years in age each, all three starting linemen returned.<ref>{{cite news |first= John|last= Harris|title= Steelers D-line aging gracefully|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_572938.html |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-06-17|accessdate=2008-06-17}}</ref> First round draft pick, Rashard Mendenhall entered camp with expectations to make an impact on the team throughout his rookie season. Pittsburgh's Willie Parker, who returned after suffering a broken leg in the 2007 season, was expected to share the load with Mendenhall.<ref>{{cite news |first= John|last= Harris|title= Expect much from Mendenhall|url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_573070.html|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-06-17|accessdate=2008-06-17}}</ref> On July 29, punter [[Daniel Sepulveda]] tore the ACL in his right leg and was placed on season-ending [[injured reserve]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Steelers' Sepulveda likely lost for the season|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_580044.html |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-07-29|accessdate=2008-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Torn ACL in right knee will keep left-footed punter out entire season|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08212/900451-66.stm|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-07-30|accessdate=2008-08-01}}</ref> The Steelers acquired [[Paul Ernster]] later in the day as a possible replacement.<ref>{{cite news |title= Steelers P Sepulveda out for season|url= http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=txsteelerssepulveda&prov=st&type=lgns|publisher= Yahoo! Sports|date= 2008-07-29|accessdate=2008-08-01}}</ref> After concluding practices at St. Vincent's, the Steelers began to practice at their facility on [[South Side (Pittsburgh)|Pittsburgh's South Side]]. Tomlin called the camp "very productive".<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Breaking camp|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08231/905178-66.stm|work= Steelers Notebook: Old familiar face joins defense|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-08-18|accessdate=2008-08-21}}</ref>

== Pre-season ==
{{Quote box
 | quote  =We're ready. I know that I feel good, and I can speak for the team. We've been practicing, gone through the preseason, and it's time to put what we've been practicing to work.
 | source = [[Willie Parker]]<ref name=Pre4Trib/><ref name=Pre4PPG/>
 | width  =250px
 | align  =right
}}
Pittsburgh opened their pre-season schedule with a 16<U+2013>10 victory over the [[Philadelphia Eagles]].<ref name=TribPS1>{{cite news |first=Scott |last=Brown |title=Steelers win preseason opener |url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_581980.html |publisher=''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-08-08|accessdate=2008-08-09}}</ref> The Steelers scored on their first possession, after driving 80&nbsp;yards on eight plays.<ref name=Ps1>{{cite web |url= http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/boxscore?game_id=29789&displayPage=tab_box_score&season=2008&week=PRE1&override=true|title= Box Score|accessdate=2008-08-09 |work= Preseason Week One|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-08-08}}</ref> Ben Roethlisberger's 19-yard touchdown pass to Santonio Holmes completed the drive.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/drivechart?game_id=29789&displayPage=tab_drive_chart&season=2008&week=PRE1&override=true|title= Drive Chart|accessdate=2008-08-09 |work= Preseason Week One|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-08-08}}</ref> In the first quarter, [[Charlie Batch]] was removed from the game after breaking his [[clavicle]].<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Batch exits Eagles game with fractured collarbone|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08221/902994-66.stm|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-08-08|accessdate=2008-08-09}}</ref> [[Jeff Reed (American football)|Jeff Reed]] converted three field goals from 20, 24, and 50&nbsp;yards.<ref name=Ps1/> [[Toronto]]'s [[Rogers Centre]] hosted the second pre-season game; it was the first pre-season game Pittsburgh played in Toronto since 1960.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.steelers.com/article/88377/|title= Steelers Release 2008 Regular Season Schedule|accessdate=2008-06-13 |publisher=Steelers.com}}</ref> Pittsburgh's starting offense played longer in the second game. Willie Parker increased his output over the first game by playing on third downs.<ref>{{cite news |first= John|last= Harris|title= First-team offense plays longer|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_583019.html?source=rss&feed=3|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-08-15|accessdate=2008-08-19}}</ref> However, the team failed run the ball consistently and struggled on defense, losing the game 24<U+2013>21.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Steelers fall to Buffalo Bills, 24-21|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08227/904445-66.stm|work= |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-08-14|accessdate=2008-08-19}}</ref> "We fell short essentially in all three phases," stated coach Tomlin after the game.<ref>{{cite news |first= Scott|last= Brown|title= Steelers take step back in Toronto|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_582973.html?source=rss&feed=9|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-08-15|accessdate=2008-08-19}}</ref>

Pittsburgh traveled to Minnesota to play the [[Minnesota Vikings|Vikings]] for their third pre-season game. The Steelers's defense held the Vikings early, led by [[Aaron Smith (American football)|Aaron Smith]] who had three tackles, including one sack, in the first quarter.<ref>{{cite news |first= John|last= Harris|title= Steelers' defense looks ready to go|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_584646.html?source=rss&feed=3|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-08-24|accessdate=2008-08-24}}</ref> The offense failed to score a touchdown, with [[Rashard Mendenhall]] fumbling twice.<ref>{{cite news |first= Scott|last= Brown|title= Steelers raise intensity against Vikings|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_584625.html|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-08-24|accessdate=2008-08-24}}</ref> Quarterback [[Byron Leftwich]], who was signed to replace the injured Batch,<ref>{{cite news |title= Steelers sign Leftwich, Culpepper as QB fill-ins |url= http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=444019|work= NFL|publisher= ''[[Sporting News]]''|date= 2008-08-09|accessdate=2008-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Steelers looking at QB Leftwich|url= http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=txsteelersleftwich&prov=st&type=lgns|work= NFL|publisher= Yahoo! Sports|date= 2008-08-09|accessdate=2008-08-09}}</ref> lead the team with 129&nbsp;yards passing.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/boxscore?game_id=29821&displayPage=tab_box_score&season=2008&week=PRE3|title= NFL GameCenter: Pre-season Week 3|accessdate=2008-08-25 |work= Box Score|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-08-23}}</ref> Jeff Reed accounted for all of the Steelers' points, kicking four field goals<U+2014>the final with 4&nbsp;seconds remaining<U+2014>to give Pittsburgh a 12<U+2013>10 victory.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Reed the only kick in offense|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08237/906742-66.stm|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-08-24|accessdate=2008-08-24}}</ref> Entering their final pre-season game the Steelers had selected every starting player except the punter.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ray|last= Fittipaldo|title= Tonight last chance for some Steelers|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08241/907598-66.stm?cmpid=sports.xml|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-08-28|accessdate=2008-08-28}}</ref> Carolina tied the game with 1:54&nbsp;remaining in regulation,<ref>{{cite web |title= NFL GameCenter: Pre-season Week 4|url= http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/boxscore?game_id=29838&displayPage=tab_box_score&season=2008&week=PRE4&override=true|work= Box Score|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-08-28|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref> but rookie [[Dennis Dixon]] lead the Steelers on a 47-yard drive,<ref name=Pre4Trib>{{cite news |first= Scott|last= Brown|title= Steelers nip Panthers with last second field goal|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_585465.html|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-08-28|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref> which was capped with Reed kicking the game winning 43-yard field goal as time expired.<ref name=Pre4PPG>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= It's a Reed-thin margin again|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08242/907939-66.stm|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-08-29|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref> After the three point victory,<ref name=Pre4AP>{{cite news |author= Associated Press|title= Reed kicks Steelers past Panthers|url= http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29838&displayPage=tab_recap|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-08-29|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref> Tomlin stated, "It has been a pleasure working with this group guys, but it is that time of year where we need to make tough decisions."<ref name=Pre4Trib/> The Steelers cut 22&nbsp;players on August 30, to bring their roster to the required 53&nbsp;player total.<ref>{{cite news |first= Gerry|last= Dulac|title= Reid, McBean among 22 cut from Steelers roster|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08244/908393-66.stm?cmpid=sports.xml|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-08-31|accessdate=2008-08-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Scott|last= Brown|title= Steelers' Reid, Drummond among final cuts|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_585768.html|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-08-31|accessdate=2008-08-31}}</ref> The following day the Steelers signed nine players from their pre-season team to the practice squad.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Nine join practice squad|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08245/908577-66.stm|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-09-01|accessdate=2008-09-04}}</ref>

