== Regular season ==
Based on [[2007 NFL season#Final regular season standings|2007 records]], the Steelers boasted the NFL's most difficult schedule in 2008,<ref name="PPG schedule">{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Steelers 2008 schedule announced|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08106/873528-66.stm |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-04-15|accessdate=2008-04-15}}</ref><ref name=Bouchette>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Ed Bouchette on the Steelers: Penguins will learn success has a price|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08160/888352-66.stm?cmpid=sports.xml |publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-06-08|accessdate=2008-06-08}}</ref> with an opponent winning percentage of .598;<ref name="ToughestSched">{{cite web |url= http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3347716|title= Steelers, Colts have toughest 2008 schedules|accessdate=2008-06-13 |date= 2008-04-16|publisher=ESPN.com}}</ref> ten games were played against teams that finished 2007 with winning records.<ref name="2007standings">{{cite web |title= Standings|publisher= NFL.com |date= 2008-03-25 |url= http://www.nfl.com/standings|accessdate= 2008-03-25}}</ref> The Steelers played each of the teams in the AFC North twice, once home and once on the road. The Steelers also faced the teams from the [[American Football Conference South Division|AFC South]] and [[National Football Conference East Division|NFC East]] divisions throughout the season.<ref name=Sub500>{{cite news |first= Mike|last= Florio|title= AFC North could produce a sub-.500 champion|url= http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=afcnorthcouldproduceasub&prov=tsn&type=lgns |publisher= ''Sporting News''|date= 2008-07-12|accessdate=2008-07-18}}</ref> Pittsburgh's matchups included the [[San Diego Chargers|San Diego]] and [[New England Patriots|New England]], who each won their division in the 2007 season.<ref name=Sub500/> The Steelers played five nationally televised primetime games,<ref>{{cite news |title= Steelers Release 2008 Regular Season Schedule|url= http://news.steelers.com/article/88377/ |publisher= Steelers.com|date= 2008-04-15|accessdate=2008-04-16}}</ref> the maximum allowed number by the NFL.<ref>{{cite news |title= Steelers get maximum number of prime time games|url= http://www.vindy.com/news/2008/apr/15/steelers-get-maximum-number-of-prime-time-games/ |publisher= Vindy.com|date= 2008-04-15|accessdate=2008-04-18}}</ref>

Entering the first week of the season, players voted Ben Roethlisberger, Hines Ward, James Farrior, and Jeff Reed team captains.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Steelers Notebook: Team elects Roethlisberger, Reed to join list of captains|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08246/908701-66.stm?cmpid=sports.xml|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 2008-09-02|accessdate=2008-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Scott|last= Brown|title= Roethlisberger among four team captains|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_585950.html?source=rss&feed=9|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 2008-09-02|accessdate=2008-09-02}}</ref> Farrior, James Harrison, and Troy Polamalu were voted to represent the Steelers at the [[2009 Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Steelers' Polamalu, Harrison, Farrior only picks for Pro Bowl|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08352/935625-66.stm?cmpid=sports.xml|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 17 December 2008|accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Three Steelers Selected to the 2009 Pro Bowl Squad|url= http://news.steelers.com/article/101166/|publisher= PittsburghSteelers.com|date= 16 December 2008|accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> James Harrison set the Steelers' franchise single-season record for sacks, surpassing [[Mike Merriweather]]'s previous record of 15&nbsp;sacks in 1984.<ref name=SackBook/> Harrison also became the first undrafted player to win the [[National Football League Defensive Player of the Year Award|NFL's Defensive Player of the Year Award]].<ref>{{cite news |author= Associated Press|title= Harrison 1st undrafted AP Defensive Player of Year|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=nfl&id=3812898|publisher= ESPN.com|date= 6 January 2009|accessdate=6 January 2009}}</ref> He was the fifth Steeler to win the award<U+2014>the first since [[Rod Woodson]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite news |author= Associated Press|title= Harrison has death grip on defensive award|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3811266|publisher= ESPN.com|date= 5 January 2009|accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> Harrison and Polamalu were also voted to the NFL's [[All-Pro]] team.<ref>{{cite news |title= Polamalu, Harrison named to AP All-Pro team|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/breaking/s_606432.html|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 9 January 2009|accessdate=9 January 2009}}</ref> The Steelers' defense tied the [[1973 Los Angeles Rams season|1973 Los Angeles Rams]] record by holding 14&nbsp;consecutive opponents under 300&nbsp;yards of total offense.<ref>{{cite news |author= Associated Press|title= Steelers ride second straight fourth-quarter rally to back-to-back division titles|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=281214033|work= Curtain Call|publisher= ESPN.com|date= 14 December 2008|accessdate=27 December 2008}}</ref> The defense finished ranked first in the league in total and passing yards given up and second in rushing yards.<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/superbowl/story?id=09000d5d80e66893&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true&icampaign=SB43_3column_3 Too early for this dominant Steelers defense to take Curtain call]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.nfl.com/stats/team?seasonId=2008&seasonType=REG&Submit=Go|title= Defensive Game Stats|accessdate=29 December 2008 |work= Statistics|publisher= NFL.com|date=28 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Alan|last= Robinson|title= Playoffs await dominating Steelers defense|url= http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=ap-steelers-defense&prov=ap&type=lgns|publisher= Yahoo! Sports|date= 29 December 2008|accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref> For the fifth time in his career [[Hines Ward]] received for over 1,000&nbsp;yards throughout the season.<ref>{{cite news |first= Scott|last= Brown|title= Ward tops 1,000-yard mark in win|url= http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/steelers/s_604806.html|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Tribune-Review''|date= 29 December 2008|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> The team's offense ranked 22nd in overall offense, 17th in passing, and 23rd in rushing.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.nfl.com/stats/categorystats?tabSeq=2&offensiveStatisticCategory=GAME_STATS&conference=ALL&role=TM&season=2008&seasonType=REG&d-447263-s=TOTAL_YARDS_GAME_AVG&d-447263-o=2&d-447263-n=1|title= Offensive Game Stats|accessdate=29 December 2008 |work= Statistics|publisher= NFL.com|date=28 December 2008}}</ref> Rashard Mendenhall was the team's only rookie to start a game; the fewest rookie starts of any team in the league.<ref name="RookieStarts">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/story?id=09000d5d80f5dc39&template=without-video-with-comments&confirm=true|title=Draft buzz: Two offensive tackles separating themselves from the pack|last=Kirwan|first=Pat|date=March 22, 2009|publisher=NFL.com|accessdate=2009-03-23}}</ref>

