===Division standings===
The 2008 season was the Steelers' seventh as members of the [[American Football Conference North Division|AFC North Division]]. Pittsburgh defended their division title from the 2007 season, which they obtained by tying the Cleveland Browns' 10<U+2013>6 record, but holding the tie-breaker with two wins over the Browns.<ref name=Bouchette/> Through 2008, Pittsburgh is the only team to have [[American Football Conference North Division#Division champions|won the AFC North]] four times, since its inception prior to the [[2002 NFL season]].<ref>The Steelers won the AFC North during the [http://www.nfl.com/standings?category=div&season=2002-REG&split=Overall 2002], [http://www.nfl.com/standings?category=div&season=2004-REG&split=Overall 2004], [http://www.nfl.com/standings?category=div&season=2007-REG&split=Overall 2007], and [http://www.nfl.com/standings?category=div&season=2008-REG&split=Overall 2008] NFL seasons.</ref> Entering the 2008 season, the Steelers were chosen to win the division by [[Sports journalism|sportswriter]] [[Ron Borges]],<ref>{{cite news |first= Ron|last= Borges|authorlink= Ron Borges|title= AFC North preview: Anticipating two-horse race|url= http://www.nfl.com/kickoff/story?id=09000d5d80a43f06&template=with-video&confirm=true|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-08-28|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref> as well as nine of 13 analysts interviewed by [[ESPN.com]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Pittsburgh Steelers (Consensus division finish: 1st)|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/preview08/team?team=pit|publisher= ESPN.com|date= 2008-08-28|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref> Four NFL.com analysts predicted that the Steelers would finish with a 10<U+2013>6 record.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ron|last= Borges|authorlink= Ron Borges|title= Steelers preview: Face challenge from long-time rival|url= http://www.nfl.com/kickoff/story?id=09000d5d80a440b2&template=with-video&confirm=true|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-08-25|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref> The Steelers finished the regular season with a record of 12<U+2013>4, going undefeated against opponents in the AFC North and winning 12&nbsp;games for the fourth season since 1979.<ref name=BrownMat>{{cite news |author= Associated Press|title= Browns game matters to Steelers' Tomlin - really|url= http://www.lancastereaglegazette.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2008812240321|publisher= ''Lancaster Eagle-Gazette''|date= 24 December 2008|accessdate=27 December 2008}}</ref> The team clinched the second seed in the AFC for the playoffs and received a bye the first week of the post-season.<ref name=SackBook>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Steelers Notebook: Sacks record doesn't ease sting of loss|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08357/936784-66.stm|work= Home field chances|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 22 December 2008|accessdate=22 December 2008}}</ref> The Baltimore Ravens finished at second place in the AFC North with an 11<U+2013>5 record, clinching a playoff seed as an AFC wild card.<ref>{{cite news |first= David|last= Ginsburg|title= Ravens enter playoffs with 27-7 win over Jaguars|url= http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap;_ylt=AtB00cLtXvNqQlkIVsFz2b5DubYF?gid=20081228033&prov=ap|publisher= Yahoo! Sports|date= 28 December 2008|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> The Cincinnati Bengals finished 4<U+2013>11<U+2013>1, winning their final three games of the season.<ref>{{cite news |first= Joe|last= Kay|title= Bengals beat Chiefs 16-6 for third straight win|url= http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap?gid=20081228004|publisher= Yahoo! Sports|date= 28 December 2008|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> The Cleveland Browns finished in the AFC North's fourth position at 4<U+2013>12;<ref name=Rout/> the team fired head coach [[Romeo Crennel]] after the season.<ref>{{cite news |title= Crennel fired after Browns' 4-win season|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3797518|publisher= ESPN.com|date=29 December 2008|accessdate=15 January 2009}}</ref>

