Pittsburgh entered week eleven with starters having missed 31&nbsp;games due to injuries.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Steelers: Injuries are never an excuse, but ...|curly=y |url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08321/928377-66.stm|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 16 November 2008|accessdate=17 November 2008}}</ref> The [[2008 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]] scored first, and led 7<U+2013>0 after the first quarter of play. On the second play of the second quarter, the Steelers' James Harrison forced a fumble in the endzone, then forced a safety by tackling the [[Marcus McNeill]] after he had recovered the fumble. Jeff Reed converted on a field goal as time expired on the first half, pulling the Steelers within two points.<ref name=PbP11>{{cite web |url= http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/playbyplay?game_id=29685&displayPage=tab_play_by_play&season=2008&week=REG11&override=true|title= Week Eleven GameCenter|accessdate=2008-11-16 |work= Play-by-Play|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-11-16}}</ref><ref name=W11Sum>{{cite web |url= http://www.nfl.com/liveupdate/gamecenter/29685/PIT_Gamebook.pdf|title= National Football League Game Summary|accessdate=2008-11-16|work= San Diego Chargers At Pittsburgh Steelers|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-11-16|format=PDF}}</ref>

Reed kicked his second field goal of the game from 41-yards to give the Steelers the lead going into the final quarter. The Chargers drove 74&nbsp;yards on 17&nbsp;plays, converting on a field goal to give them the lead again, with 6:45 remaining. On the Steelers' ensuing drive, the offense drove 73&nbsp;yards and Reed converted on his third field goal of the day, giving the Steelers an 11<U+2013>10 lead with 15&nbsp;seconds remaining in regulation. The Chargers attempted to score on their final play, but Troy Polamalu forced and recovered a fumble, returning it for a touchdown.<ref name=PbP11/><ref name=W11Sum/> The call was reversed when the officials ruled that San Diego had made an illegal forward pass. After the game, head referee [[Scott Green (American football official)|Scott Green]] admitted that the touchdown should have been counted.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://post-gazette.com/pg/08322/928592-66.stm |title=Steelers Notebook: Official admits mistake on play |first=Ed |last=Bouchette |date=17 November 2008 |accessdate=17 November 2008 |publisher=''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= Associated Press|authorlink= Associated Press|title= Referee says officials errantly voided Steelers TD|curly=y |url= http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80c930b0&template=with-video-with-comments&confirm=true|publisher= NFL.com|date= 17 November 2008|accessdate=17 November 2008}}</ref> With the touchdown not counted the final score kept Pittsburgh under the 5&nbsp;point [[spread betting|spread]] by which they were favored, and resulted in over $32&nbsp;million being lost in bets.<ref name="Errant call">{{cite web |url= http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/27768483/|title= Errant call in Steelers-Chargers affects betting|accessdate=2008-11-17|publisher= [[NBC Sports]]|date= 2008-11-17}}</ref> The game was the first game in NFL history to end with a final score of 11<U+2013>10.<ref>{{cite news |first= Alan|last= Robinson|title= Steelers beat Chargers in NFL<U+2019>s first 11-10 game|curly=y |url= http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap?gid=20081116023&prov=ap|publisher= Yahoo! Sports|date= 17 November 2008|accessdate=17 November 2008}}</ref>

