Although guaranteed the second seed in the AFC Tomlin stated, "It is a big week for us."<ref name=BrownMat/> Willie Parker's 34-yard touchdown run in the second quarter was the Steelers longest run of the season.<ref name=Rout/> With less than two minutes left in the first half, Ben Roethlisberger was hit by D'Qwell Jackson and Willie McGinist and had to be immobilized and carried off the field after suffering from a [[concussion]].<ref>{{cite news |author= Associated Press|title= Roethlisberger taken off field on stretcher|url= http://msn.foxsports.com/nfl/story/8997078/Roethlisberger-taken-off-field-on-stretcher|publisher= Fox Sports (USA)|date= 28 December 2008|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> Byron Leftwich replaced Roethlisberger and scored the Steelers second touchdown of the game to give the Steelers a 14<U+2013>0 lead at halftime.<ref name=PbP17>{{cite web |url= http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/playbyplay?game_id=29779&displayPage=tab_play_by_play&season=2008&week=REG17&override=true|title= Week Seventeen GameCenter|accessdate=2008-12-28|work= Play-by-Play|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-12-28}}</ref><ref name=W17Sum>{{cite web |url= http://www.nfl.com/liveupdate/gamecenter/29779/PIT_Gamebook.pdf|title= National Football League Game Summary|accessdate=2008-12-28|work=Cleveland Browns at Pittsburgh Steelers|publisher= NFL.com|date= 2008-12-28|format=PDF}}</ref>

Pittsburgh scored the only points of the third quarter when Jeff Reed converted his sole field goal attempt of the game. The Steelers added two touchdowns in the final quarter<U+2014>on a Gary Russell rush and Tyrone Carter's return of his second interception of the game.<ref name=PbP17/><ref name=W17Sum/> "We were so upset we had to practice on Christmas, we had to take it out on the Browns," said Larry Foote after the victory.<ref name=Rout>{{cite news |author= Associated Press|title= Big Ben gets concussion; Steelers rout Browns 31-0|url= http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap?gid=20081228023&prov=ap|publisher= Yahoo! Sports|date=28 December 2008|accessdate=28 December 2008}}</ref>

== Post-season ==
{{main|NFL playoffs, 2008<U+2013>09}}
Their 12<U+2013>4 regular season record gave the Steelers a second place finish in the AFC. Along with the Tennessee Titans, who finished with the best record in the AFC, the Steelers received a [[Bye (sports)|bye]] during the opening week of the post-season.<ref>{{cite web|title= Playoff picture|url= http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3711069|publisher= ESPN.com|date= 28 December 2008|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> The 2008 season was the seventh of the past 16 that the Steelers were the first or second seed in the AFC entering the playoffs<U+2014>never winning the Super Bowl during those seasons.<ref>{{cite news |first= Alan|last= Robinson|title= Bye bye? Playoff bye not always good for Steelers|url= http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=ap-steelerswithabye&prov=ap&type=lgns|publisher= Yahoo! Sports|date= 1 January 2009|accessdate=2 January 2009}}</ref> Pittsburgh defeated the San Diego Chargers in the Divisional round, giving up a franchise post-season low of 15&nbsp;rushing yards.<ref>{{cite news |first= Gene|last= Collier|title= Steelers throttle Chargers' run game|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/09012/941198-66.stm|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 12 January 2009|accessdate=12 January 2009}}</ref> The victory was head coach Mike Tomlin's first in the post-season.<ref>{{cite news |first= Ed|last= Bouchette|title= Steelers beat Chargers, 35-24, advance to AFC championship|url= http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/09011/941186-66.stm?cmpid=sports.xml|publisher= ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette''|date= 11 January 2009|accessdate=12 January 2009}}</ref> The Steelers defeated the Baltimore Ravens in the [[AFC Championship Game]]. The Steelers won [[Super Bowl XLIII]] over the NFC Champion Arizona Cardinals on February 1.

